      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Chemistry insight\n\nThe data beautifully illustrate the Irving–Williams trend, which arises from the interplay of ionic radius, ligand-field stabilisation energy (LFSE), and the Jahn–Teller distortion that uniquely favours Cu²⁺ (d⁹). The dominant features — a steady rise from Mn²⁺ (d⁵, zero LFSE) through Ni²⁺ (d⁸, maximum octahedral LFSE among the series) to the Cu²⁺ peak, followed by a drop at Zn²⁺ (d¹⁰, zero LFSE) — are all clearly present. The only minor nuance is that Zn²⁺ sits slightly *above* Co²⁺ rather than below it; this is occasionally observed with small monodentate N-donors and reflects the flexible coordination geometry of the d¹⁰ ion, which can adopt a tetrahedral arrangement that is particularly favourable for ammonia.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes). All values at 25 °C, I = 0 mol L⁻¹, aqueous solution.*",
        "claims": [
          {
            "start": 4,
            "end": 21,
            "text": "Chemistry insight",
            "claim_type": "filler",
